The v3.1 profile's `gpu_memory_utilization` value is **0.55**.

**Why it was picked (D-29):**

The v3 profile had `gpu_memory_utilization: 0.88`, which was determined by an automated KV-bisection finder (`scripts/find_kv_budget.py`) that ran 10 iterations from 0.75 up to 0.93 (all clean, zero preemptions, zero OOM). The 0.88 value was chosen with a 5% safety margin below the highest clean value of 0.93.

However, this KV-finder was optimized for "no preemption" at the vLLM level and **didn't account for OS-side RAM headroom** on the DGX Spark's 128 GB UMA (Unified Memory Architecture) pool. At 0.88 utilization, the emmy-serve process consumed too much of the shared memory, leaving only ~4.6 GiB free in `free -h` with 7.2 GiB of swap in use — essentially starving the OS.

The D-29 change to 0.55 was a **user lock** targeting an emmy-serve footprint of ~50–70 GB, leaving **>40 GB of system RAM free** on the 128 GB DGX Spark UMA pool. This was validated in the phase3.1-01-walkthrough run, which showed 42 GiB available post-restart (vs 4.6 GiB on v3) — a 9× improvement in system headroom.

The `max_num_batched_tokens` was also reduced from 16384 to 8192 (D-29) to further reduce the CUDA workspace footprint, while still staying above the "interactive latency" threshold documented in STACK.md.
